    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-06-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-06-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="284"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d284">
                <head>284. National Security Decision Memorandum 67<note n="1" type="source"
                        xml:id="d284fn1">Source: National Archives, <persName corresp="#p_NRM1"
                            >Nixon</persName> Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1"
                            >NSC</gloss> Files, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Institutional
                        Files (<gloss target="#t_H1">H</gloss>-Files), Box <gloss target="#t_H1"
                            >H</gloss>–217, National Security Decision Memoranda, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSDM1">NSDM</gloss> 67. Secret; Nodis; Exclusively Eyes Only.
                        A copy was sent to the Chairman of the Joint Chiefs of Staff.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-06-25">June 25, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="to">
                    <head>TO</head>
                    <item>The Secretary of State</item>
                    <item>The Secretary of Defense</item>
                </list>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Military Supply Policy Toward Greece</item>
                </list>
                <p>Based on the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> discussion of June 17<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d284fn2">See <ref target="#d283">Document 283</ref>.</note> and the
                    memorandum from the Chairman of the <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Under
                    Secretaries Committee, “Resumption of Deliveries of Suspended Military Shipments
                    to Greece,”<note n="3" xml:id="d284fn3">
                        <ref target="#d278">Document 278</ref>.</note> the President has approved
                    the following as the principal elements in a course of action to implement the
                    decision to resume arms shipments to Greece: <list>
                        <item>—Prime Minister <persName corresp="#p_PLCG1">Papadopoulos</persName>
                            may be told in advance and in strictest confidence of the <gloss
                                target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> intention to resume military shipments
                            after, in our judgment, such resumption will no longer seriously
                            jeopardize the Foreign Military Sales bill and assuming legislative
                            authority for such resumption.</item>
                        <item>—In this connection, he may be told that our target for resumption is
                            about September 1.</item>
                        <item>—The Prime Minister should be further informed that in connection with
                            the resumption it is anticipated that there will be further specific
                            steps which we can cite as further evidence of progress toward full
                            constitutional government. The Prime Minister can be told that the
                                <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> takes at face value and accepts
                            without reservation his assurances on moving toward parliamentary
                            democracy.</item>
                    </list>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0768" n="724" xml:id="pg_724"/>
                <p>The <gloss target="#t_US1">U.S.</gloss> Ambassador in Greece should be given
                    discretion on the question of timing of (a) the delivery of the letter from the
                    President to the Prime Minister; (b) advice to the Prime Minister of our
                    intention to resume shipments; and (c) informing him of the necessity of
                    specific further evidence of progress toward constitutional government in
                    Greece.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">
                            <hi rend="strong">Henry A. Kissinger</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
